{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"76e82313-0ada-43ab-af8a-b293f9ad0b19","content":"On macOS, the OS automatically captures crash reports — no `createdump` needed.\n\n**Look for `.ips` crash logs here:**\n\n```\n~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/\n```\n\nFiles are named like `YourApp_2026-04-25-013153_MacBook.ips`. You can also find them in **Console.app → Crash Reports**.\n\n**For a full core dump** (disabled by default):\n\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\n./your-nativeaot-app   # reproduce the crash\n# Core file lands in /cores/core.<pid>\n```\n\n> **Note:** NativeAOT does **not** bundle `createdump` (unlike CoreCLR). The `.ips` crash log is usually the fastest path — it contains the faulting thread, all thread backtraces, and register state. You can symbolicate the `.NET runtime frames` using `atos` and debug symbols from the Microsoft symbol server.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b7af15b9-e192-4b8b-83ee-46127ccb2224","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET app on macOS, specifically without `createdump`. This is a knowledge question — I don't need to search a codebase. Let me answer directly.\n\nOn macOS, when a process crashes, the OS automatically generates a crash report (`.ips` file) in:\n\n- `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (user-level)\n- `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (system-level)\n\nFor NativeAOT apps, `createdump` is not bundled (unlike CoreCLR), so you rely on the OS-level crash reporting.\n\n\nI could also enable core dumps with `ulimit -c unlimited`, though they're disabled by default — but the `.ips` crash logs are really what you'll want to use here.","outputTokens":459,"requestId":"6405:25505C:158C3C2:1907782:69EC1988"},"id":"ba8a1814-7645-455e-ae65-8bb3215b4216","timestamp":"2026-04-25T01:32:04.369Z","parentId":"440885e7-a2a2-4604-9916-bbe251f042cd"}
